We aim to combat the decline of holm oak groves in the Tramuntana region, addressing the effects of climate change and livestock management. The project involves planting new trees and dispersing acorns in a reforested area on Son Torrella's farm.

This planting site has an area of around 7 hectares. Though its not the biggest planting site, it counts on an interesting biodiversity. It has little gradients and counts on important sized trees from previous plantations here.

In this part of the land we are building an educational forest, where we are planting native species of the Yungas with the objective that visitors first learn to recognize each species before entering the forest. Its area is approximately 3 hectares.

This 17 hectares planting area is located between the river and the main road. It is a very degraded area that needs recovery. It is a key zone for the local fauna due to its proximity to the river but the existing vegetation does not help protect it.

This is the place where we will be planting in the rainy season of this year (from october 2020, to march 2021 , also december 2021).
It's a lot next to the river so it is very rich in biodiversity. The estimated area is a bit more than 4 hectares.

This planting site is found to be highly deteriorated, which means it will need an important enrichment job. We did find some ecologically important species, but when it comes to structure, the area is scarce. Its estimated area is about 9 hectares.

The plantation period of the year 21/22 was mainly in this site, counting on an area of 26 hectares. The main species planted here are Cedro, since its main goal is to regain structure as soon as possible, accompanied by other species of the top stratum.

This project area in the Amuru district in the North of Uganda contains 17 group clusters, these are usually key local villages, and a list of 549 different groups of local farmers.

Until recently this was a tree-lined country lane that provided biodiversity and wind shelter for local wildlife. These trees had to be felled due to safety concerns. This project is to replace this area with native boundary hedges.

The land is part of the Blue Cross Animal Sanctuary, whose owners want to plant trees to improve the environment for local people and the animals. The planting by community groups and schools will be a combination of native woodland and hedgerows.

5000 native trees on a large scale (13ha) site near Glasgow, part of Cathkin Braes Country Park. 1120 trees are planted by local community groups and ITF volunteers; the other trees are planted by local school children. Maintained by Glasgow City Council

Trees replace those lost by Ash Dieback + continue woodland conversion from commercial coniferous to native broadleaf woods. This part of Wales (Pembrokeshire) is largely treeless (deforested for agriculture). New forests are vital for people + wildlife.

The project plants + protects native saplings by creating a mature woodland with a broad range of habitats. The protected land ensures community engagement with volunteers and the people working together to plant and steward the saplings as they mature

After planting 1000 trees in 2021, the local landowners and community groups are planting more trees along public byways and footpaths. 
This will provide habitat for local wildlife, as well as providing shelterbelts for the local fruit farms.

Habitat restoration of a 126-acre site, located on a working farm that offers environmental education together with residential stays for disabled and other vulnerable groups, which will be involved in planting and learning about the newly planted trees.

Creation of a hedgerow around a community orchard. This will protect from strong winds, contribute towards increasing pollen for insects, berries for birds, and habitats and food for over 300 species, including the  endangered species, red squirrel.

Transformation of a vacant and derelict industrial park into a multi-use community space to increase social value and native restoration. Will also be used to grow local food and teach the community about how they can learn and gain from nature.

Creation of a mosaic of copses and hedgerows at one of the largest wildlife rescue and rehabilitation centres in the UK. They now purchased 20 acres of land to create new habitats, an open access visitor centre and a new wildlife hospital.

Blackcap is one of the many sites managed by the National Trust that collectively form the South Downs National Park. The Trust is looking to enhance Blackcap through the creation of wood pasture, clump planting, and hedgerows across the site.

Banbury Trees, a very committed community volunteer group are working with local landowners who are keen to welcome the public on to their land to plant and enjoy the trees and hedgerows. They will also be involved with the tree care and maintainance.

The Astall Manor Kitchen Garden (registered Community Interest Company) plants a 220m hedgerow, creating a wildlife friendly boundary hedge + connecting existing areas of high biodiversity. A network of volunteers will help plant and maintain the hedge.

The 54 ha site (project phase 2 with TN) lies on the edge of the Cotswolds Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty (AONB), a former farm now owned by the Blue Cross Rehoming Centre. Native woodland + hedgerow species will be planted by local community groups.

This small holding site lies directly beside a well known local woodland which attracts walkers + cyclists. The owner wants to extend the natural environment with hawthorn hedges and willow trees (habitat for the local red squirrels and other wildlife).

11 acre smallholding, providing high quality, sustainable food and a space for nature to thrive (shelter belts around both fields + pockets of woodland areas). They want to plant more native trees for increased shelter and more habitat for local wildlife

Foxholes farm is a progressive farm wanting to improve the biodiversity of the site and the connectivity between fields. The community will be involved in the hedge planting and will have opportunities to visit the hedges in the coming years.

This famous beauty spot on the South Downs National Park is owned by the National Trust. The planting will enhance the landscape with additional copses, wood pastures + hedgerows. This is a publicly-accessible spot, well enjoyed due to its fantastic view

Outstanding 20th-century garden, set around a romantic house + ruins, in beautiful woodland. Mixture of neo-classical ruins + well-kept gardens makes this site very popular spot. This project aims to enhance the landscape with planting of native hedgerow

Part of a larger plan to develop the Primary Academy Wildlife Reserve & Community Garden within the West Marsh area of Grimsby, creating a bio-diverse area in the school that improves the local biodiversity and supports the children to appreciate nature.

This NF is part of the Greater Yellowstone Area (some of the most rugged + scenic areas in the US). Project supports recovery from wildfires + spruce budworm infestation, re-establishes a seed source for future regeneration and improves forest resilience

This NF extends from majestic Rocky Mountains to vast grasslands, suffered a severe wildfire in 2020 burning 208,913 acres near Cameron Peak (largest wildfire in Colorado). Reforestation will stabilize soil + halt erosion after flash flooding in 2021.

The project in these 2 NF consists of Native Habitat Restoration. Longleaf pine was once the largest forest ecosystem in the USA, but today reduced to 5% of its historic range. The species planted in this NF are long-lived and highly resistant to fire.

Native habitat restoration, insect and disease recovery, and wind recovery in Chippewa National Forest. Planting of native species to provide multiple benefits of forest restoration and resilience enhancement.

The project is planting 20,000 trees. The planting area burned in the 2015 Corner Creek Fire. This area is important for wildlife and provides valuable fish habitat, including the headwaters of the South Fork of the John Day River.

In 2020, the lightening-caused White Rive Fire burned 17,400 acres, with just over half of the fire
occurring on Mt. Hood National Forest. The Forest Service is targeting high severity burn areas to
help re-establish healthy fire-adapted forest habitats.

This project increases species diversity and helps re-establish historical forest stands. Removal of local conifer species (white pine and hemlock) after 2 centuries of industrial logging has weakened resilience and resistance in these Great Lakes forest
This project re-establishes mixed conifers devastated by the 2020 Lake Wildfire, first reported on Aug. 12, burning 31,089 acres (12,581ha) near lake Hughes.

The Slater (2020) and McCash Fires (2021) burned 45,000 ha within the Indian and Elk Creek watersheds of the Klamath National Forest. Replanting a mix of native seedlings restores watersheds and revives resistant forests as wildlife habitat.

Largest state forest in Georgia (14k ha). Focus on enhancing a native ecosystem that faced recent diseases, insects, and drought. This work provides soil stability, improves water quality, enriches recreational forest use, and supports wildlife species.
